VALUES ('28fde7a2-c4fc-815a-9614-d8540f871785', 'Meat Stock', 'üç≤', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'https://attachments.convertkitcdnn2.com/1350002/4633fb64-e17d-40bf-9392-29d73f7247dc/meat-stock-2023.pdf', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '["1 whole chicken - including feet + neck","2 carrots","1 medium onion","1 tbsp peppercorns","1 heaping tbsp sea salt","herbs: rosemary, parsley, thyme, oregano, etc."]', 'Break the chicken down into smaller pieces, so that the surface area of the joints will contact the water. Include feet and neck, 1 or 2 as the minimum, and more if you have them. Place pieces in the dutch oven, add one qt water per every 1lb meaty bone. Add chopped carrots and onions (optional) & 1 tbsp sea salt to the pot. Bring to a boil, keep boiling for 15 minutes. Skim any "impurities" that have risen to the top. This looks like brown foam. Bring to a simmer and cover for 1.5- 2 hours. The more you skim, the clearer the consistency of the stock.
Next, remove the chicken. If you would like, place it in a bath of ice water. An ice bath will stop the cooking immediately and allow you to take the shredded chicken off the bone more quickly. Otherwise, it will be too hot to touch, and you''ll have to wait for about 30-45 minutes.
If you pour the hot stock into your glass jars, this will sterilize the jar, and the meat stock will be good for 7-10 days in your fridge.
If you want to turn your meat stock into soup: Add your vegetables: onions, carrots, mushroom, radish, broccoli (no stems), cauliflower (no stems), and bring to a simmer for 45 minutes. Add some chicken (you will likely have leftovers for salad or stirfries), skin, and "nibbly bits". Add in any additional meat, egg yolks, and salt to taste.
It is good in the freezer for up to 1 year and the fridge for about one week. Leave the breasts out of the stock and save them for frying at a later time.', 1760731829780, 1760731829780, 0);
